868,0.05909607,0.05067556,-0.03983033,-0.00544158,0.06059531,0.00929497,-0.04959948,-0.00968332,0.07050409,-0.03609475,0.02919954,-0.03740282,0.02984941,0.00731364,-0.00500056,-0.06648475,-0.03296123,0.01383741,-0.04964477,-0.03028389,0.00604490,-0.02968918,-0.09401057,0.00896845,0.01670327,0.04358683,0.02451413,-0.08029439,-0.03863275,-0.04782319,0.04270523,0.01159835,-0.04994640,0.01638565,-0.07620595,0.04233508,0.01762431,0.01651227,0.10088273,-0.03470888,-0.00253054]',E'Triggering Another Route\n\nSometimes `pass` is not what you want, instead, you would like to get the\nresult of calling another route. Simply use `call` to achieve this:\n\n```ruby\nget ''/foo'' do\n  status, headers, body = call env.merge("PATH_INFO" => ''/bar'')\n  [status, headers, body.map(&:upcase)]\nend\n\nget ''/bar'' do\n  "bar"\nend\n```\n\nNote that in the example above, you would ease testing and increase\nperformance by simply moving `"bar"` into a helper used by both `/foo` and\n`/bar`.\n\nIf you want the request to be sent to the same application instance rather\nthan a duplicate, use `call!` instead of `call`.\n\nCheck out the Rack specification if you want to learn more about `call`.','{"source": "sinatra", "version": "4", "language": "ruby", "title": "Sinatra", "section_title": "README", "url": "https://github.com/sinatra/sinatra/blob/main/README.md", "topics": "sinatra,ruby,README", "categories": "web,ruby,rest"}');
